    <h3 class="cag-h3">Where the Grey Ranks Against Every Talker</h3>
    <p>Above the Grey there is nothing; below it, Amazons talk well with a musical delivery, Eclectus stay clear but quieter, and a budgie can technically bank more words in a mumble no one can parse. For usable, contextual speech, the Grey is the ceiling.</p>
    <h4 class="cag-h4">Why Clarity Beats Raw Vocabulary</h4>
    <p>Buyers do not want a bird that mutters two hundred blurred words; they want the phone-ring, the greeting and the joke delivered clearly, at the right moment. That is the Grey's real advantage, and it is why our African Grey facts guide keeps returning to contextual use over sheer count.</p>
    <h5 class="cag-h5">Citation: the talking-parrot rankings</h5>
    <p>Across mainstream avian references and pet-care roundups from Lafeber, PetMD and The Spruce Pets, the African Grey is placed first for talking ability, with Amazons the usual runner-up.</p>
    <h6 class="cag-h6">Data note: how we compiled the ranking</h6>
    <p>Our order reflects the consensus of those published rankings plus our own placements, weighted toward clarity and contextual use rather than maximum vocabulary — a single number of words is the metric that most misleads first-time buyers.</p>
